{{Infobox newspaper |name = Law & Business |logo = |image = ZiB logo.jpg |caption = |type = weekly [[newspaper]] |format = |owners = |publisher = |editor = |chiefeditor = |assoceditor = |maneditor = |newseditor = |managingeditordesign = |campuseditor = |campuschief = |opeditor = |sportseditor = |photoeditor = |staff = |foundation = {{Start date|1991}} |political = |language = [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Russian language|Russian]] |ceased publication = |headquarters = Ukraine, Kiev, Krasnotkatska St. 42-a |circulation = |sister newspapers = |ISSN = |oclc = |website = [http://zib.com.ua/ zib.com.ua] }}
'''''Law & Business''''' (Russian: Закон и Бизнес; Ukrainian: Закон і Бізнес) is Ukraine’s [[weekly newspaper|weekly]] [[Legal newsletter|legal newspaper]]. It circulates to [[lawyer]]s, [[judge]]s, and [[general counsel]] from state offices. The paper reports [[legal information]] of national importance, including legal news for the [[business sector|business]] and [[private sector]]s, [[court decision]]s, [[verdicts]], practitioners' columns, and coverage of [[legislation|legislative issues]].
The newspaper was founded in 1991, and as of 2011 its [[Newspaper circulation|print circulation]] was about 16,000. It is published in the Russian and Ukrainian languages. Both language editions and its [[archive]]s are freely available [[online]].
{{DEFAULTSORT:Law and Business (Ukrainian newspaper)}} [[Category:Legal newspapers]] [[Category:Ukrainian-language newspapers]] [[Category:Russian-language newspapers published in Ukraine]] [[Category:Weekly newspapers]] [[Category:Publications established in 1991]] [[Category:1991 establishments in Ukraine]]

'''Queen bee syndrome''' was first defined by G.L. Staines, T.E. Jayaratne, and C. Tavris in 1973.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1114&context=articles |title=New Evidence on Gender Differences in Promotion Rates: An Empirical Analysis of a Sample of New Hires |author=Francine D. Blau and Jed DeVaro |publisher=[[Cornell University]] ILR School |page=16 |year=2007 |accessdate=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718172929/http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1114&context=articles |archive-date=2011-07-18 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> It describes a woman in a position of authority who views or treats subordinates more critically if they are female. This phenomenon has been documented by several studies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Office queen bees hold back women's careers |author=Roger Dobson and Will Iredale |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |date=31 December 2006 |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1265356.ece |access-date=2010-05-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604213932/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1265356.ece |archive-date=2011-06-04 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Ellemers |first=N. |last2=van den Heuvel |first2=H. |year=2004 |title=The underrepresentation of women in science: differential commitment or the queen bee syndrome? |journal=[[British Journal of Social Psychology]] |volume=43 |issue=September |pages=313–338 |pmid=15479533 |doi=10.1348/0144666042037999}}</ref> In another study, scientists from the [[University of Toronto]] speculated that the queen bee syndrome may be the reason that women find it more stressful to work for women managers; no difference was found in stress levels for male workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Women find working for female bosses more stressful |author=Chris Irvine |newspaper=[[telegraph.co.uk]] |date=23 September 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/3064811/Women-find-working-for-female-bosses-more-stressful.html |access-date=2018-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713000648/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/3064811/Women-find-working-for-female-bosses-more-stressful.html |archive-date=2018-07-13 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> An alternate, though closely related, definition describes a queen bee as one who has succeeded in her career, but refuses to help other women do the same.<ref>{{cite news |title=WOMEN IN MEDICINE FIND A NEED FOR SUPPORT |author=Judy Klemensrud |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=13 April 1981 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/13/style/women-in-medicine-find-a-need-for-support.html?sec=health}}</ref>
==In adolescence== [[Middle school]] and [[high school]] seems to be the place in which the queen bee syndrome is born.{{Explain|reason=If the syndrome in the workplace is the product of cultural influences, and not a clinical condition in a person, how can it stem from adolescence?|date=October 2018}}{{cn|date=October 2018}} Vicious [[bullying]] of teen girls can sometimes be found in the interactions of adolescent girls, often with the operations spearheaded by one individual, who has as of late been dubbed the "[[Queen bee (sociology)|queen bee]]." In recent years, research has shown that adolescent girls form (often small) groups called cliques, which are often created based on a shared characteristic or quality of the members such as attractiveness or popularity. Association with such a group is often wanted by those who are part of the larger, all encompassing group, such as a class or school. It is the association with these groups that brings an individual similar treatment.<ref>Closson, L. M. (2009). Aggressive and Prosocial Behaviors Within Early Adolescent Friendship Cliques</ref>
==Notable cases== A popular example of a movie based on girls with queen bee syndrome is the 2004 film, ''[[Mean Girls]]''. The authorized biographer of [[Margaret Thatcher]], [[Charles Moore (journalist)|Charles Moore]], stated in an interview his belief that the former British prime minister had herself suffered from the syndrome.<ref>{{cite web |last=Somerset |first=Guy |title=Charles Moore interview |url=http://www.noted.co.nz/archive/listener-nz-2013/charles-moore-interview-the-extended-version/ |magazine=[[New Zealand Listener]] |accessdate=26 February 2017 |date=6 June 2013 |quote=Partly there was a genuine problem about the talent within the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Tory Party]] at that time – it was not great. But I think also she did suffer, as her critics say, from what they call the queen bee syndrome: she thought, 'I can do it, why can't others? It's not for me to fish around to find the right women, I'm just going to get the nearest good person to hand' ... All her comments, even as a young woman about other women in letters to [her sister] [[Muriel Cullen|Muriel]], tend to be competitive and sometimes quite critical. She didn't have much personal solidarity with women if they were also ambitious. She was very close to some women who were in subsidiary positions, such as her diary secretaries – she's extremely fond of them and very nice to them - but I don't think you'll find much closeness to any female equal. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227151552/http://www.noted.co.nz/archive/listener-nz-2013/charles-moore-interview-the-extended-version/ |archive-date=2017-02-27 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref>
==In the workplace== Recent research has postulated that queen bee syndrome may be a product of certain cultural influences,<ref name=Derks2011>{{cite journal |doi=10.1348/014466610X525280|pmid=21884548|title=Do sexist organizational cultures create the Queen Bee?|journal=British Journal of Social Psychology|volume=50|issue=3|pages=519–535|year=2011|last1=Derks|first1=Belle|last2=Ellemers|first2=Naomi|last3=Van Laar|first3=Colette|last4=De Groot|first4=Kim}}</ref><ref name=Derks2011b>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0956797611417258|pmid=21873568|title=Gender-Bias Primes Elicit Queen-Bee Responses Among Senior Policewomen|journal=Psychological Science|volume=22|issue=10|pages=1243–1249|year=2011|last1=Derks|first1=Belle|last2=Van Laar|first2=Colette|last3=Ellemers|first3=Naomi|last4=De Groot|first4=Kim|url=https://lirias.kuleuven.be/handle/123456789/487084|type=Submitted manuscript}}</ref> especially those related to the modern workplace.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}
Researchers have hypothesized<ref name=Derks2011b /> that queen bee behavior may be developed by women who have achieved high workplace positions within their respective fields as a way to defend against any gender bias found in their cultures. By opposing attempts of subordinates of their own sex to advance in career paths, women displaying queen bee behavior try to fit in with their male counterparts by adhering to the cultural stigmas placed on gender in the workplace. Distancing themselves from female subordinates can allow for the opportunity to show more masculine qualities, stereotypically seen as more culturally valuable and professional. By showing these supposedly important masculine qualities, women displaying queen bee behavior seek to further legitimize their right to be in important professional positions as well as attaining job security by showing commitment to their professional roles.<ref name=Derks2011 /><ref name=Derks2011b />
